<HEADLINE>
<P>
CALIFORNIA IN BRIEF; 
</P>
<P>
NORTH TUSTIN; 
</P>
<P>
DAY-CARE CENTER SUED OVER MISHAP 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
From Times Staff and Wire Reports 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
The parents of a 2-year-old boy left paralyzed and brain-damaged after tumbling 
into a swimming pool at an unlicensed day-care center in the Orange County 
community of North Tustin have sued the center's owners, the county and the 
state, contending that stricter regulation of the facility could have prevented 
the accident. Christy Kolbet, 40, and Derek Weston, 29, of Santa Ana, seek 
unspecified damages for the accident March 30 at the Cowan Heights home of 
Diane and Orvel Brooks. Jonathan Derek Weston and two other children fell into 
the Brooks' pool when the couple's daughter, Carol, left them unattended. A 
14-month-old boy, Arthur M. Griese, died about 24 hours after Orvel Brooks 
pulled him from the water. Another 2-year-old, Melissa Dianne Polsfoot, 
suffered permanent brain damage. 
</P>
</TEXT>
