NATION; 
</P>
<P>
CUTTER GROUNDS IN LAKE STORM 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
From Times Wire Services 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
<P>
COPPER HARBOR, Mich. 
</P>
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
A Coast Guard cutter ran aground today in 6-foot waves off Michigan in Lake 
Superior, injuring at least three crewmen and causing extensive damage, 
authorities reported. 
</P>
<P>
Two helicopters and three cutters helped rescue the 50 crew members who were 
forced to abandon the 180-foot Mesquite, said Petty Officer Frank Jennings, a 
spokesman at the Coast Guard's Great Lakes district office in Cleveland. 
</P>
<P>
Those flown to a hospital included a crew member with a broken arm and one who 
apparently suffered a heart attack, according to Jennings, who said the nature 
of the third injury was not immediately available. 
</P>
<P>
The World War II-vintage cutter, a buoy tender based in Charlevoix, Mich., hit 
a submerged ledge at 2:30 a.m. about three-fourths of a mile off Keweenaw Point 
near Copper Harbor in Michigan's Upper Peninsula, Jennings said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
