<P>
ARCTIC AIR PUTS BITE ON NORTH, STRETCHES TO FLA. 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By Associated Press 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Arctic air howled across the nation's northern tier today, and winter's bite 
was felt as far south as Florida, where a possible frost kept citrus growers 
checking their trees and sun lovers all bundled up. 
</P>
<P>
Heavy snow buried parts of Maine, West Virginia and the Great Lakes states. 
Some snowbelt areas received nearly two feet of winter's white by early today. 
</P>
<P>
Schools were closed in two counties in West Virginia and in northern areas of 
Maine. 
</P>
<P>
In the Deep South, cold winds blew across Georgia. Temperatures, with the wind 
chill factor, plummeted as low as 10 degrees in Atlanta. 
</P>
